partnerships: aXcess Asia/Pacific Cambodia, aXcess Africa Senegal - Desert Springs Team St Lou
comment:
THE worst Annual Report to fill out in my over 42 years of Alliance ministry - on several levels ... a total botched job with the technology, lack of appropriateness to our specific ministry, and others.

It's not "wired" for small town, rural church ministry - we don't fit into the boxes you offer - and yet we are joyfully worshipping our Lord, connecting with our community, discipling people, and enabling Alliance missions to move forward - at our level of ministry / in ways culturally appropriate to our congregation and community.  Yes, we need to rethink how we're doing ministry - and we are - but in the end it may not look like what you're looking for - it may end up looking more like the "COVID Church."  The concepts promoted are good and we need to seriously consider them, maybe replace some of what we're doing, but I feel this Report is more of a "heaping on" rather than simply a "reporting of." You asked, I answered - with a deep, deep love for the Alliance - but also some concern.

STMEvent: Yes - we used Alliance Missions video
comment: For the past seven years we have been functioning in partnership with an independent Vietnamese congregation (that resulted from a Vietnamese Alliance church split), and have reported their members as adherents to our church.  As of November 2022, they have been accepted as a new congregation in the Vietnamese District; so we are reporting them as a new church plant, and they will be reporting their own membership numbers and giving information from now on.  However, the partnership continues, and a number of their members continue to attend our English-language service and give to our General Fund; the Anglo congregation is doing children's and youth ministry and Sunday School for their kids; and we are continuing to do an ESL outreach together.  So if our reported numbers look weird this year, that's the reason why!

comment: This year was wild. Year two of a pandemic. We as a church community started the year fully online and ended the year in a new space, meeting in person. Over the course of this year we changed locations, began to meet in person and the Lord delivered us a new meeting space that meets all our needs. As the pastor of this community, it may have added some grey hair, but the hand of the Lord was evident. We feel some great momentum as we are exiting this pandemic (hopefully) and are excited about where the Lord has placed us. It was a wild ride but we learned a lot. We can now easily pivot to a digital only service, we REALLY appreciate being back together and we are thankful that everyone recovered from bouts with Covid. The Lord is good and we are looking forward to see where He leads in 2022.     Pastor Louis
